<p><a name="Three-dimensional_digital_art" id="Three-dimensional_digital_art"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Angle_of_view&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Three-dimensional digital art">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Three-dimensional digital art</span></h2>
<p>Displaying <a href="/wiki/3d_graphics" title="3d graphics" class="mw-redirect">3d graphics</a> requires <a href="/wiki/3d_projection" title="3d projection" class="mw-redirect">3d projection</a> of the models onto a 2d surface, and uses a series of mathematical calculations to render the scene. The angle of view of the scene is thus readily set and changed; some renderers even measure the angle of view as the focal length of an imaginary lens. The angle of view can also be projected onto the surface at an angle greater than 90°, effectively creating a fish eye lens effect.</p>
<p><a name="Cinematography" id="Cinematography"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Angle_of_view&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Cinematography">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Cinematography</span></h2>
<p>Modifying the angle of view over time, or <i>zooming</i>, is a frequently used <a href="/wiki/Cinematic_techniques" title="Cinematic techniques">cinematic technique</a>.</p>
<p><a name="Video_games" id="Video_games"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Angle_of_view&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Video games">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Video games</span></h3>
<p>As an effect, some <a href="/wiki/Subjective_viewpoint" title="Subjective viewpoint" class="mw-redirect">first person</a> games, especially racing games, widen the angle of view beyond 90° to exaggerate the distance the player is travelling, thus exaggerating the player's perceived speed. This effect can be done progressively, or upon the activation of some sort of "turbo boost." An interesting visual effect in itself, it also provides a way for game developers to suggest speeds faster than the <a href="/wiki/Game_engine" title="Game engine">game engine</a> or <a href="/wiki/Computer_hardware" title="Computer hardware" class="mw-redirect">computer hardware</a> is capable of displaying. Some examples include <i><a href="/wiki/Burnout_Paradise" title="Burnout Paradise">Burnout Paradise</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Grand_Theft_Auto_IV" title="Grand Theft Auto IV">Grand Theft Auto IV</a></i>.</p>
<p>Players of <a href="/wiki/First-person_shooter" title="First-person shooter">first-person shooter</a> games sometimes set the angle of view of the game, widening it in an unnatural way (a difference of 20 or 30 degrees from normal), in order to see more peripherally.</p>
<p><a name="References_and_notes" id="References_and_notes"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Angle_of_view&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: References and notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">References and notes</span></h2>
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> One exception is technical photography involving <a href="/wiki/View_camera#Movements" title="View camera">view camera movements</a>, in which the optical axis of the lens may not be aligned with the center of the frame. The photographer must ensure that the angle of coverage of the lens is large enough to cover the frame in this case.</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFNeil_Wayne_Northey1916">Neil Wayne Northey (September 1916). Frank V. Chambers. ed. "<a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=kiUEAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA481&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=y5FyR7W6LJ3stAODw6CeBw#PPA477,M1" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=kiUEAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA481&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=y5FyR7W6LJ3stAODw6CeBw#PPA477,M1" rel="nofollow">The Angle of View of your Lens</a>". <i>The Camera</i> (Columbia Photographic Society) <b>20</b> (9)<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=kiUEAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA481&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=y5FyR7W6LJ3stAODw6CeBw#PPA477,M1" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=kiUEAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA481&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=y5FyR7W6LJ3stAODw6CeBw#PPA477,M1" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=kiUEAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA481&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=y5FyR7W6LJ3stAODw6CeBw#PPA477,M1</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Angle+of+View+of+your+Lens&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Camera&amp;rft.aulast=Neil+Wayne+Northey&amp;rft.au=Neil+Wayne+Northey&amp;rft.date=September+1916&amp;rft.volume=20&amp;rft.issue=9&amp;rft.pub=Columbia+Photographic+Society&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DkiUEAAAAYAAJ%26pg%3DPA481%26dq%3D%2522field-of%2Bview%2522%2B%2522focal%2Blength%2522%2Bcamera%26lr%3D%26as_brr%3D1%26ei%3Dy5FyR7W6LJ3stAODw6CeBw%23PPA477%2CM1&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Angle_of_view"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFErnest_McCollough1893">Ernest McCollough (1893). "<a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=eCkAAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA402&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera+tangent+%22length+of+the+plate%22&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=X51yR8HBDo6eswOpiZieBw" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=eCkAAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA402&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera+tangent+%22length+of+the+plate%22&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=X51yR8HBDo6eswOpiZieBw" rel="nofollow">Photographic Topography</a>". <i>Industry: A Monthly Magazine Devoted to Science, Engineering and Mechanic Arts</i> (Industrial Publishing Company, San Francisco): 399–406<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=eCkAAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA402&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera+tangent+%22length+of+the+plate%22&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=X51yR8HBDo6eswOpiZieBw" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=eCkAAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA402&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera+tangent+%22length+of+the+plate%22&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=X51yR8HBDo6eswOpiZieBw" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=eCkAAAAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA402&amp;dq=%22field-of+view%22+%22focal+length%22+camera+tangent+%22length+of+the+plate%22&amp;lr=&amp;as_brr=1&amp;ei=X51yR8HBDo6eswOpiZieBw</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Photographic+Topography&amp;rft.jtitle=Industry%3A+A+Monthly+Magazine+Devoted+to+Science%2C+Engineering+and+Mechanic+Arts&amp;rft.aulast=Ernest+McCollough&amp;rft.au=Ernest+McCollough&amp;rft.date=1893&amp;rft.pages=399%E2%80%93406&amp;rft.pub=Industrial+Publishing+Company%2C+San+Francisco&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DeCkAAAAAMAAJ%26pg%3DPA402%26dq%3D%252